Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.49,0:00:07.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The most crucial moment in life is during decision making.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.45,0:00:13.91,Default,,0,0,0,,The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.91,0:00:19.95,Default,,0,0,0,,But also instilled \Nnumerous lessons on how to live.{unsure, lit is "for the sake of living, precepts, numerous left behind"}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.37,0:00:31.38,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,700)\c&H0007DF&\fs100\b1\bord0\blur1}Animentary\N{\b\c&HE0DBF3&}Decision
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.71,0:00:42.98,Default,,0,0,30,,Wit is your weapon{honestly no clue what is megurase here, deepl says "rack one's brain"}\NRemember to use your head{智恵をめぐらせ 頭を使え}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.98,0:00:50.95,Default,,0,0,30,,Repress your anguish, \NIf you are a man{悩み抜け抜け 男なら}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.95,0:00:59.24,Default,,0,0,30,,One decision is enough \NTo make others cry or laugh{泣くも笑うも 決断ひとつ}
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.24,0:01:06.69,Default,,0,0,30,,If you win, don't hold your head high, \NIf you lose, don't cry{勝っておごるな 敗れて泣くな}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.69,0:01:14.55,Default,,0,0,30,,Men, don't you ever let others see your tears{男 涙は見せぬもの}
Comment: 0,0:01:34.91,0:01:34.95,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.57,0:01:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,May 1942.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.04,0:01:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Aimed at securing the hold on Rabaul bases, \Nand opening a prospect for attacking the Australian north,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.58,0:01:49.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Port Moresby Operation was started. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operation_Mo}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.63,0:01:55.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Its first step was the capture of Tulagi island \Nby the special landing party that started{don't like to use this word twice in two consequtive sentences but i think it looks alright} from Rabaul.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.42,0:01:56.23,Default,,0,0,0,,However,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.23,0:02:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,having been warned in advance of the Japanese attack,\Nthe Australian garrison{actually "reserve corps" but I think they mean this} had already been evacuated.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.52,0:02:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,The island was entirely deserted. {completely empty (of a residence, etc.); vacant; deserted​}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.37,0:02:11.38,Default,,0,0,0,,6:30 am on May 4th.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.38,0:02:17.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Upon learning of the Japanese occupation of Tulagi Island, \Nthe US Mobile Task Force commander, Rear Admiral Fletcher
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.17,0:02:20.57,Default,,0,0,0,,immediately dispatched the air wings \Nof the Lexington carrier, {lit: sent flying shipborne planes}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.57,0:02:22.58,Default,,0,0,0,,ordering them to commence the attack.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.87,0:02:44.22,Sign,,0,0,240,,{\c&HF7F3F6&\b1\blur1\bord0}Episode 8 \N {\fs120} {Naval }Battle of the Coral Sea {珊瑚海海戦}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.25,0:03:14.19,Default,,0,0,0,,At that time, on the Japanese side, \Nin his Rabaul {island base }headquarters,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.19,0:03:17.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the Commander-in-Chief of the 4th Fleet, \NVice Admiral Inoue, {Shigeyoshi Inoue (井上 成美, Inoue Shigeyoshi, December 9, 1889 – December 15, 1975) was an admiral in the Imperial Japanese Navy during World War II. He was commander of the Japanese 4th Fleet and later served as Vice-Minister of the Navy. A noted naval theorist, he was a strong advocate of naval aviation within the Japanese Navy. He subsequently relocated his headquarters to Rabaul for Operation Mo, intended to occupy Port Moresby. However, after the Japanese defeat at the Battle of the Coral Sea in May 1942, he was relieved of his command in October, and returned to Japan to become commander of the Imperial Japanese Naval Academy.}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.15,0:03:22.14,Default,,0,0,0,,executing the overall command of this operation, \Nwas expecting reports from the front line. {supreme command; direction over all} {/waiting for}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:26.54,0:03:27.64,Default,,0,0,0,,What are the losses? {/damage}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.64,0:03:31.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Destroyer - 1, minesweepers - 2, \Nas well as one submarine chaser{ were sunk}.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.19,0:03:33.71,Default,,0,0,0,,But if we were attacked solely by carrier-based planes... {again, shipborne} {/the fact that ... means}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.71,0:03:37.61,Default,,0,0,0,,It means that the American Mobile Fleet \Nhas advanced deep into the Coral Sea, around here.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.13,0:03:38.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.90,0:03:43.61,Default,,0,0,0,,The enemy Mobile Fleet must definitely be \Nwithin 200 nautical miles of Tulagi.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.82,0:03:51.75,Default,,0,0,0,,However, our own Mobile Fleet is currently refueling \Nabout 360 nautical miles north of Tulagi Island.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.39,0:03:56.56,Default,,0,0,0,,One might conclude the enemy \Nis fairly well-informed about our operations, {/movements}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.56,0:03:58.25,Default,,0,0,0,,but that's also their weakness. {weak point (to take advantage of); weakness}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.25,0:04:03.77,Default,,0,0,0,,As long as the enemy knows \Nthat our operation's objective is Port Moresby right here,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:03.77,0:04:07.13,Default,,0,0,0,,their movements are rigidly confined \Nto the Coral Sea. {the enemy can't move out of ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.81,0:04:10.14,Default,,0,0,0,,A telegram from the Combined Fleet \NCommander-in-Chief.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.14,0:04:13.68,Default,,0,0,0,,The elusive American carriers \Nthat have been pestering us since the war's outbreak - {lit: that we had trouble catching/were embarrassed}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:13.68,0:04:16.44,Default,,0,0,0,,dealing with them now \Nwould be immensely rousing for our morale. {lit: this time for sure, destroying them we'd be most happy}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.17,0:04:23.53,Default,,0,0,0,,On May 6, with orders to deal a decisive blow \Nto the American Mobile Task Force, {/destroy}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.53,0:04:29.08,Default,,0,0,0,,under the leadership of Rear Admiral Takagi Takeo, \Nthe Japanese Mobile Task Force advanced into the Coral Sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.89,0:04:34.03,Default,,0,0,0,,From the bridge of the brand new carrier Zuikaku, \Nthe pride of the Japanese Navy, {young and energetic; up-and-coming; new and excellent; newly produced; up-and-comer}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.03,0:04:37.50,Default,,0,0,0,,together with Rear Admiral Takagi, \NCommander of the 5th Carrier Division {I know division is usually land unit but that's what it's called in wiki}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:37.50,0:04:40.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Rear Admiral Hara was overseeing the operation. {lit is "staring at the path" but I've no clue what it means, was just "were staring out from the bridge" in HA's; Takagi was promoted to vice admiral on 1 May 1942. He was commander of the carrier task force (Shōkaku and Zuikaku) in "Operation Mo". Thus he was also senior Japanese commander at the Battle of the Coral Sea; During World War II, Hara was the commanding officer of the Fifth Carrier Division of the Imperial Japanese Navy for the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor. His command contained the two brand-new aircraft carriers Zuikaku and Shōkaku.}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.47,0:04:41.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Will we be able to spot them?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.86,0:04:43.74,Default,,0,0,0,,That's something I'm fearing myself. {sounds not very brave but I can't come up with a better word in english that'd not blow away the CPS, maybe "have apprehensions?"}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.74,0:04:47.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Tomorrow night, upon passing by \Nthe southern tip of San Cristobal Island, {no clue what's this shi after myouni}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.88,0:04:50.10,Default,,0,0,0,,we would enter the Coral Sea from the east.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.10,0:04:52.76,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like looking for a single fish in the entire Pacific Ocean. {HA: "It's like looking for a loach in the Pacific Ocean.", loach is a type of fish, seemed to obscure to leave in - Paul; I have nothing better than this to offer, I don't seem to know what else this bujou/dojou can be but it's really particular and obscure indeed to pick loach, and it doesn't seem to be a part of any proverb either so I double Paul there; also it may be worth noting loach  is a freshwater fish and a very small one at that, so it can't be in the ocean, but that doesn't make sense: they know the enemy is there; might replace with something move conventional, like "a needle in the haystack" - Perevo}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.76,0:04:54.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly so.
